ANTHRAX - INDIA (22): (ASSAM) CARCASS DISPOSAL
**********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: 15 Aug 2016
Source: Times of India [edited]
http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/guwahati/Tests-show-anthrax-role-in-cattle-deaths/articleshow/53704685.cms


Kaziranga National Park authorities on Sunday [14 Aug 2016] said anthrax might have killed the 7 Asiatic wild buffaloes whose carcasses were found inside the protected area on Wednesday [10 Aug 2016]. Preliminary tests conducted on the carcasses have revealed traces of anthrax. The results of the final test will be out in a few days, said park director Satyendra Singh. "We are waiting for the final report. We sent the samples to the College of Veterinary Science in Guwahati on 12 Aug 2016. It takes almost 5 days for the final report to come," he added.

Kaziranga divisional forest officer Suvasish Das said the carcasses were treated with formalin and other chemicals before being incinerated. This, he said, would prevent the spread of anthrax. "We have not come across any more buffalo deaths after Wednesday [10 Aug 2016]. We followed due procedure for disposing of the carcasses," he added.

Kaziranga, a World Heritage Site about 250 km from here, lost over 300 animals, including 22 rhinos, during last month's [July 2016] floods.

